	faithHeading="Faith and the Bible in Mexico"
	faithBodyHtml={`<p>Mexico is one of the most Christian nations on earth. About <strong>78% are Roman Catholic</strong> &mdash; one of the largest Catholic populations anywhere &mdash; and roughly <strong>10% are Protestant or evangelical</strong> and growing, especially in the south. All told, nearly <strong>88% of Mexicans are Christian</strong>.</p><p>Faith is everywhere: in fiestas and processions, in the devotion to Our Lady of Guadalupe, in the cross over countless doorways. The beloved <strong>Reina-Valera</strong> (especially the 1960 revision) has carried the Spanish Bible for generations, alongside newer versions like the NVI.</p><p>And yet, for all this devotion, many Mexicans have never read the Scriptures for themselves, and God can feel distant &mdash; approached through ritual and intermediaries rather than known as a Father. The need is not a first encounter with religion. It is to meet, in the Bible Mexico already reveres, the Father who has been near all along.</p>`}
	sources={[
		{ label: 'Religion in Mexico (2020 census / US State Dept.)', url: 'https://www.state.gov/reports/2022-report-on-international-religious-freedom/mexico' },
		{ label: 'Reina-Valera (Wikipedia)', url: 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reina_Valera' },
	]}
	painsHeading="What pains Mexico"
	painsIntroHtml={`Behind the color and the faith, Mexican families carry deep wounds &mdash; and it is into these exact aches that the Father&rsquo;s heart speaks.`}
